House, which
are that the president has
enormous power,

20:00.098 --> 20:04.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but he also is enormously
limited in his power,
that there are lots of
institutions, the press,

20:04.937 --> 20:07.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the courts, the Congress, that
can constrain
him.

20:07.639 --> 20:09.541 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's interesting.

20:09.575 --> 20:12.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think you were telling us
earlier today
that it was almost like there
were two operations

20:12.544 --> 20:14.313 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going on at the same time.

20:14.346 --> 20:18.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has one operation around him
to sort of
protect him, make sure he's all
right, protect

20:18.784 --> 20:23.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his brand, you said, and then,
on the other
hand, the operation to keep the
business of

20:23.088 --> 20:24.890 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the presidency going.

20:24.923 --> 20:30.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL SCHERER: Yes, he is
enormously focused
on his personal reputation and
experience

20:30.329 --> 20:32.264 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in office.

20:32.297 --> 20:36.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think he spends a lot of
time watching
TV at night, seeing how things
are being digested.

20:36.068 --> 20:43.175 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's an incredibly erudite media
critic, which
we saw during the campaign.

20:43.208 --> 20:48.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is really separate, I
think, from
what the business of the
presidency is, which

20:48.313 --> 20:50.882 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is running a very large and
complicated government.

20:50.916 --> 20:52.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, he's involved in those
issues, too.

20:52.784 --> 20:57.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not as if he's not engaged
in the details
of, you know, getting Obamacare
repeal through

20:57.556 --> 20:59.458 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Congress or something like that.

20:59.491 --> 21:03.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's just that I think, more
than other presidents,
he's spending a lot of time
focused on this

21:03.428 --> 21:04.896 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
other thing.

21:04.930 --> 21:08.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he does have staff around
him who are
essentially personal staff.

21:08.267 --> 21:12.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're not staff that are
plugged into the
hierarchy of a traditional White
House.

21:12.638 --> 21:16.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're not reporting directly
to the chief
of staff, and they help him with
that.

21:16.174 --> 21:19.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And any inkling
-- of course,
this was Monday, before we knew
about the

21:19.511 --> 21:23.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
firing of FBI director -- any
inkling something
like that was coming down?

21:23.982 --> 21:27.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL SCHERER: There was no
discussion of
the FBI director, Comey.

21:27.953 --> 21:34.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The only inkling was, he
returned several
times to his frustration about
the press not

21:34.960 --> 21:40.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reporting that his wiretapping
tweet of a
few weeks ago saying that Barack
Obama wiretapped

21:40.299 --> 21:45.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
me in Trump Tower, he still
believes, he still
argues, was true, even though
Director Comey

21:45.737 --> 21:48.006 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
testified that there was no
evidence...

21:48.040 --> 21:49.007 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

21:49.041 --> 21:50.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That he was
wiretapped.

21:50.042 --> 21:51.009 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He argues that that...

21:51.043 --> 21:52.244 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

21:52.277 --> 21:53.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MICHAEL SCHERER: And his
argument is a little
complicated.

21:53.145 --> 21:54.980 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is saying wiretapping is in
quotes.

21:55.013 --> 21:58.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It includes any unmasking by any
officials
of anyone in my campaign, which
may have happened.

21:58.984 --> 22:04.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said he believes that, if
an official
was unmasked in a foreign
intelligence tap,

22:04.156 --> 22:06.091 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that would count as wiretapping.

22:06.124 --> 22:12.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a stretch, but his anger at
-- his feeling
of being wronged by the way
that's been discussed,

22:12.097 --> 22:16.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and I think that includes what
the FBI director
said before Congress, was very
apparent.

22:17.002 --> 22:23.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Michael Scherer,
"TIME" magazine,
fascinating.

22:23.108 --> 22:28.080 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL SCHERER: Thank you.

22:28.113 --> 22:33.118 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you.

22:33.151 --> 22:37.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Until this week, much of the
country had never
heard of Rod Rosenstein.

22:37.255 --> 22:41.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But he's been thrust into the
spotlight following
the firing of James Comey.

22:41.493 --> 22:46.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Late today, leaders of the
Senate issued an
unusual invitation to invite him
to meet with

22:46.665 --> 22:49.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
all 100 senators.

22:49.034 --> 22:53.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Margaret Warner brings us up to
speed on the
man charged with overseeing the
investigation

22:53.372 --> 22:57.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into Russia's interference in
last year's
presidential election.

22:57.342 --> 23:02.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: The author of
the fateful
James Comey memo appeared on
Capitol Hill

23:02.447 --> 23:04.216 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today.

23:04.249 --> 23:08.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Deputy Attorney General Rod
Rosenstein met
with the top Republican and
Democrat on the

23:08.754 --> 23:10.155 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Senate Intelligence Committee.

23:10.188 --> 23:14.326 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Afterwards, they said Comey's
firing wasn't
discussed.

23:14.359 --> 23:17.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But Democratic Vice Chair Mark
Warner remained
skeptical.

23:17.763 --> 23:19.598 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

23:19.631 --> 23:22.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK WARNER (D), Virginia: I
think it was
a productive session, but I
still have concerns

23:22.634 --> 23:30.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about Mr. Rosenstein in terms of
his role
in the Comey departure.

23:30.876 --> 23:35.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Rosenstein has
said privately
he didn't initiate Comey's
firing.

23:35.614 --> 23:40.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still, there are now nearly as
many questions
for the Justice Department's
number two as

23:40.619 --> 23:45.023 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there are for the ousted FBI
director himself.

23:45.056 --> 23:48.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rosenstein graduated Harvard Law
School in
1989.

23:48.160 --> 23:52.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In 1997, he became an assistant
U.S. attorney
in Maryland.

23:52.864 --> 23:58.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In 2005, President Bush
appointed him the
state's top federal prosecutor,
a post he

23:58.270 --> 24:00.472 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
held until this year.

24:00.505 --> 24:04.509 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In January, President Trump
nominated him
for deputy attorney general.

24:04.543 --> 24:08.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At his hearing, senators of both
parties praised
him.

24:08.413 --> 24:10.315 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

24:10.348 --> 24:13.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLES GRASSLEY (R), Iowa: I
know of no reason
to question his judgment, his
integrity, or

24:13.251 --> 24:14.219 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
his impartiality.

24:14.252 --> 24:16.021 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

24:16.054 --> 24:19.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BEN CARDIN (D), Maryland: Rod
Rosenstein has
demonstrated throughout his long
career the

24:19.157 --> 24:21.359 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
highest standards of
professionalism.

24:21.393 --> 24:26.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: The Judiciary
Committee also
received dozens of letters
supporting his

24:26.231 --> 24:28.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
nomination.

24:28.166 --> 24:34.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One signed by more than 120
former U.S. attorneys
said Rosenstein -- quote --
"epitomizes the

24:34.506 --> 24:36.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ideal Department of Justice
lawyer."

24:36.608 --> 24:39.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He was confirmed 94-6.

24:39.778 --> 24:44.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
One no vote, Connecticut
Democrat Richard
Blumenthal, who said he'd use
every possible

24:45.016 --> 24:50.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tool to block any nominee for
the position,
unless there was a special
counsel assigned

24:50.088 --> 24:53.024 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to the Russia investigation.

24:53.058 --> 24:58.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Attorney General Jeff Sessions
recused himself
from the Russia probe in March,
so when Rosenstein

24:58.363 --> 25:02.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was sworn in two weeks ago, that
authority
fell to him.

25:02.934 --> 25:05.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Margaret Warner.

25:05.437 --> 25:10.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now let's
take a closer
look at what lies ahead for that
Russia investigation.

25:10.141 --> 25:11.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
William Brangham is back with
that.

25:11.943 --> 25:15.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Comey's firing
has sparked
accusations that the president
is trying to

25:15.347 --> 25:20.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
derail the Russia investigation,
or at least
exert more control over its
direction.

25:20.318 --> 25:23.488 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, where does that
investigation go from
here?

25:23.522 --> 25:26.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Frank Montoya Jr. spent 26 years
in the FBI.

25:26.725 --> 25:30.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He oversaw national security and
counterintelligence
probes.

25:30.195 --> 25:32.264 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he joins us from Salt Lake
City.

25:32.297 --> 25:36.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Amy Jeffress worked on
national security
investigations as counselor to
former Attorney

25:36.902 --> 25:41.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
General Eric Holder and at the
U.S. Attorney's
Office in Washington, D.C.

25:41.740 --> 25:43.208 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

25:43.241 --> 25:44.509 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Frank Montoya, I would like to
start with
you.

25:44.543 --> 25:48.747 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have been talking with a lot
of FBI agents.

25:48.780 --> 25:51.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Give us a sense of how they are
responding
to Comey's firing.

25:51.716 --> 25:55.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRANK MONTOYA JR., Former FBI
Official: You
have heard a lot of descriptions
already in

25:55.387 --> 25:58.890 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
terms of being stunned or
gut-punched.

25:58.924 --> 26:03.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those are, I think, are apropos
of the sense
of -- or the feeling that's in
the organization

26:03.929 --> 26:06.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right now, that it really did
come out of
the blue.

26:06.898 --> 26:08.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they're struggling with it.

26:08.266 --> 26:11.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, at the same time, they're
all professionals
at what they do.

26:11.403 --> 26:13.838 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They know how to put the mission
first.

26:13.872 --> 26:15.640 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they will continue to move
forward.

26:15.674 --> 26:19.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Do any of the
agents that
you have spoken with believe
that the firing

26:19.277 --> 26:20.245 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was justified?

26:20.278 --> 26:21.813 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
FRANK MONTOYA: Absolutely not.

26:21.846 --> 26:23.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This was, again, out of the
blue.

26:23.715 --> 26:28.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was one of those things
where, even amongst
those few critics in the
organization, the

26:28.219 --> 26:34.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
independence of the FBI -- and
Jim Comey represented
that well -- the independence of
the FBI is

26:34.759 --> 26:36.528 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
utmost in their minds.

26:36.561 --> 26:39.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the only way that they feel
like they
can go forward and do the work
that they do.

26:39.764 --> 26:41.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Amy Jeffress,
I will turn
to you.

26:41.866 --> 26:43.735 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What was your reaction to
Comey's firing?

26:43.768 --> 26:47.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY JEFFRESS, Former Justice
Department Official:
I absolutely agree with what
Frank just said

26:47.238 --> 26:53.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and what Andy McCabe testified
to in Congress
today, which is that my
perception is that

26:53.745 --> 26:57.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Director Comey did have the
confidence of
the agency.

26:57.682 --> 27:02.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And certainly the actions he
took last summer
and in the fall were
controversial, and many

27:02.787 --> 27:07.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people can criticize certain
aspects of what
he did, but I don't think anyone
can say that

27:07.525 --> 27:11.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he wasn't independent or that he
wasn't trying
to do what he perceived as the
right thing

27:11.763 --> 27:15.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the -- at every step of the
investigation.

27:15.567 --> 27:21.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And my sense is that the agents
really felt
like he was supportive of them
and that he

27:21.039 --> 27:25.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would have their back and that
he wanted to
let them do their jobs
professionally and

27:25.944 --> 27:26.911 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
independently.

27:26.945 --> 27:30.982 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, I think morale is not good.

27:31.016 --> 27:33.284 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Agents are disappointed at his
firing.

27:33.318 --> 27:36.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I also agree with Frank that
the agents
will continue to do their jobs
as best they

27:36.788 --> 27:38.657 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can, because that's their
tradition.

27:38.690 --> 27:44.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Amy, what did
you make of
Deputy Attorney General Rod
Rosenstein's letter

27:44.129 --> 27:49.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that catalogued a whole slew of
criticisms
of Comey's handling of the
Hillary Clinton

27:49.734 --> 27:51.503 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
investigation?

27:51.536 --> 27:56.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY JEFFRESS: Well, the letter
contained some
criticisms that I think many
people would

27:56.775 --> 27:58.476 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
agree with.

27:58.510 --> 28:05.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, on the other hand, I didn't
see it as
any real justification for
Director Comey's

28:05.583 --> 28:07.452 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
firing.

28:07.485 --> 28:11.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't think that that
firing was handled
in a way that any career
Department of Justice

28:11.723 --> 28:15.760 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
prosecutor, which Rod Rosenstein
is, would
have liked to see it handled.

28:15.794 --> 28:18.830 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It just -- it didn't go
according to the process
that should have been followed.

28:18.863 --> 28:19.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I'm going to
ask you...

28:19.864 --> 28:20.932 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

28:20.965 --> 28:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANK MONTOYA: I agree on that
one, by the
way.

28:21.833 --> 28:22.801 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I would like to interject there.

28:22.834 --> 28:25.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, this was really about
independence.

28:25.303 --> 28:29.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's where the rubber
meets the road
on this and what is causing us a
lot of concern

28:29.708 --> 28:31.443 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
right now within the FBI.

28:31.476 --> 28:36.147 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Frank,
sticking with you
then, what does this mean for
the ongoing

28:36.181 --> 28:37.549 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Russia investigation?

28:37.582 --> 28:41.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, there has got to be a
new head of
the FBI put into place.

28:41.219 --> 28:44.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What does this firing and the
subsequent events
mean for that probe?

28:44.923 --> 28:47.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANK MONTOYA: Well, Andy McCabe
put it very
succinctly today.

28:48.026 --> 28:49.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It will move forward.

28:49.260 --> 28:52.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The men and the women of the FBI
will do the
right thing.

28:52.197 --> 28:54.399 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They will continue in their
mission.

28:54.432 --> 28:59.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that includes investigating
the interference,
Russian interference, into our
democracy and

28:59.571 --> 29:01.873 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
all things associated with that.

29:01.906 --> 29:05.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is a lot of determination
to get to
the bottom of this.

29:05.410 --> 29:10.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was unfortunate that Jim is
not going to
be at the head of this
investigation anymore,

29:10.115 --> 29:14.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but they will continue to do
what it is they
have sworn an oath to do, and
that is to pursue

