X. Snow, who uses her art to
help her overcome

52:09.826 --> 52:11.528 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a speech impairment.

52:11.561 --> 52:16.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JESS X. SNOW, Artist: My
parents, they grew
up in a government in China that
had a lot

52:16.733 --> 52:18.568 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of censorship.

52:18.602 --> 52:25.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when I was discovering art
for the first
time, I felt like there was a
door that opened

52:25.108 --> 52:31.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in my family's ancestry, and I
could be -- I
could be the first person to
tell our story

52:31.648 --> 52:33.583 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
without the fear of censorship.

52:33.617 --> 52:40.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I felt like me reclaiming my
voice in
the U.S. and overcoming my
stutter created

52:40.724 --> 52:52.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a doorway into being able to
share my family's
story to the public.

52:52.869 --> 52:58.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would get bullied a lot in the
classroom,
and people would finish my
sentences for me.

52:58.542 --> 53:04.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Through my art, I was able to
see myself overcoming
my stutter.

53:04.047 --> 53:09.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I found a community of poets of
color when
I was in college.

53:09.719 --> 53:17.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that was the first time I
was able to
share my poetry on a stage.

53:17.460 --> 53:21.097 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When that happened, I just
stopped.

53:21.131 --> 53:24.401 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I stopped stuttering.

53:24.434 --> 53:27.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Imagination is daring to love
what is not
in front us.

53:27.404 --> 53:33.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what then is immigration, if
not imagination
given a destination?

53:33.810 --> 53:35.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Migration is magic.

53:35.245 --> 53:38.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course they're afraid of all
who possess
it.

53:38.782 --> 53:43.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of my work is inspired by
the idea that
migration is natural.

53:43.920 --> 53:49.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I just think a border drawn
upon the earth's
skin is extremely unnatural.

53:49.326 --> 53:56.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when people's families and
lives are policed
by borders, the result is that
young immigrants

53:56.099 --> 54:00.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
grow up feeling like their
identities are
divided and they have to give
up, like, their

54:00.971 --> 54:04.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
